data.title: Schrader called into Newcastle Rebels to replace injured Royal
data.meta_description: There is a strange sense of deja vu surrounding Colby Schrader’s call-up to the Newcastle representative rugby league...
data.text:
Colby Schrader.

There is a strange sense of deja vu surrounding Colby Schrader’s call-up to the Newcastle representative rugby league team.

The Maitland Pickers captain has been named as the starting prop for Saturday’s NSW Country Championship final against Canberra after being unavailable for Newcastle’s semi-final win on July 9.

Schrader comes in for Kurri Kurri skipper Jesse Royal, who was ruled out with an ankle injury following Rebels training at Dangar Park on Monday night.

It was 12 months ago that Schrader was given the nod for last year’s final after being 18th man for much of the campaign.

The prop replaced Pickers teammate Adam Withyman and took a place on the bench in the 2011 decider as Newcastle produced a drought-breaking 28-24 victory against then four-time defending champions Illawarra.

Schrader and the rest of the Newcastle squad will be hoping for a similar result when they face the men from the nation’s capital in Canberra on Saturday.

Pickers pair Billy Towers and Marco Delapena, both on debut in the Newcastle side, are both being monitored with ankle injuries with final

medical checks to take place at training tonight.

Matt Ireland from South Newcastle has been put on stand by as

back-up should any player be forced to

withdraw.

Pickers playmaker Jade Porter retains his position at halfback along with NSW Country incumbent Jacob Sinclair in the Newcastle squad released yesterday.

NEWCASTLE REBELS: Sam Wooden (Cessnock), Justin Smith (Western Suburbs), Simon Williams (Western Suburbs), Steve Gordon (Western Suburbs), Chris Pyne (Cessnock), Riley Brown (Cessnock), Jade Porter (Maitland), Colby Schrader (Maitland), Terrence Seu Seu (Cessnock), Brendan Hlad (Cessnock), Daniel Metcalf (Cessnock), Jacob Sinclair (Maitland), Alec Fata (Cessnock), Marco Delapena (Maitland), Billy Towers (Maitland), Simon Allen (Macquarie), Michael O’Shea (Cessnock), Jace Delaney (Central Newcastle ).
